Russell Sage Foundation 
105 East 22d Street
New York City
Mrs. Russell Sage, President
Robert W. De Forest, Vice President
Cleveland H. Dodge, Treasurer
John M. Glenn 
General Director
Miss Helen M. Gould
Robert C. Ogden
Mrs. William B. Rice
Miss Louisa Lee Schuyler
Alfred T. White
Cable Address
"Sagefond" New York
April 13, 1911 [handwritten: "below"]
Professor Graham Taylor,
87 East Lake Street,
Chicago, Ill.
Dear Taylor:
A committee composed of Devine, Frank Mason North, Ernest Abbott and myself are considering chossing [sic] Rev. Charles S. Macfarland as secretary of the Social Service Commission of the Federal Council of Churches [handwritten in margin: "1 : 3 2"].  Please let me know what you think his qualifications are for such a position.  He has impressed me very much.  If convenient, please send me a night letter, collect.  I shall be much obliged.
Sincerely yours,
John M. Glenn
Macfarland is able, well read, resourceful has unclear intelligence, initiative & admirably: vision, writes & speaks well, is widely acquainted and related unclear timidly, unclear among business and labor unclear around Boston and in Connecticut.  Judgement unclear good as far as tested.

Russell Sage Foundation
130 East 22d Street
New York City
John M. Glenn,
General Director
June 19, 1920
Dr. Graham Taylor
The Chicago Commons
Chicagoo [sic] Ill.
Dear Dr. Taylor:
I am sending you a formal letter addressed to the School, notifying you of the grant from the Foundation to the School and its conditions.  Our trustees are not willing to make a larger grant at this time.  Their only reason for making a grant is the emergency in which the School finds itself.
Sincerely yours
J. M. Glenn
We have not been able to get the minutes of the Conference ready yet.  They are being written.  We enjoyed having you for the evening!

One Lexington Avenue
May 2d. 1938.
Dear Graham Taylor,
This is just a belated line to say that it gives me much pleasure to know that you are still able to enjoy a birthday & birthday greetings -- I wish I could present mine in person & see you in the flesh.  I would enjoy that greatly.  I hope the day has been a happy one and will leave cheering memories behind for you to meditate on.  The inspiration & joy that have fallen

Caption-Abstract: Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)
Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)
Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)

element_texts.text: Completed

to my lot from association with that wonderful group of settlement workers of which you were an important member cannot be measured.  I feel immensely grateful to you & the rest of them.  I know that you miss the others immensely.  The chief drawback to long life is the loss of old friends, as I know from experience altho' I am only 80.  I am fortunate, however, in being in good trim physically & fairly good mentally!  I won't venture to say the same of my mental calibre!  Mrs. Glenn is also very well except that she is somewhat crippled by arthritis.  She wishes to share in sending good wishes & very affectionate greetings to you.
Yours always
John M. Glenn

Mrs. Edgar B. Gordon
2206 Van Hise Avenue
Madison, Wisconsin
March 20, 1937  
Dear Dr. Taylor,
Your book, which I finished reading -- as soon as it came -- revived many memories that I had almost forgotten.  My contact with the Commons dates back farther than Edgar's for I taught in the Old Commons on Union St. you may remember, and watched the building of the new Commons.  
Thank you so much for your inscription in the front -- it makes it doubly appreciated.  
Affectionately  
Edna Gordon

Maxwell S. Green
4408 Ellis Avenue
Chicago, Illinois
May 27, 1930 
Dear Dr. Taylor 
Returning from the City Club dinner given in your honor, the following familiar lines run thro my mind as pointing a moral to us who listened to the recital of your life time of good deeds:
'Lives of great men all remind us  
We can make our lives sublime,  
And, departing, leave behind us  
Footprints on the sands of time.' 
With best wishes for many more years of 'Happy Warrior' service, 
Sincerely yours  
Maxwell S. Green

Connecticut Mutual Life
Insurance Company.
Hartford.
[In different hand:] From Jacob L. Green 
President Conn. Mutual Life Ins. Co. Prominent Citizen. & in Episcopal Church
[Main text:]
July 18, 1892
My dear Dr. Taylor,
If your unclear call is a call of the Spirit to the spirit I have working to Day: no one has.  Perhaps I haven't anyhow.  But I am going to be a little presuming for Hartford's sake.  If it be a call of spiritual feebleness & destitution to spiritual fullness & strength, from weakness to strong manhood, there is nothing to be said but Godspeed.  But I know the west fairly well from having lived in it & having close relations with it ever since.  and so I imagine the matter admits of review & argument.  
And will you have patience to let me say two things: You will have more personal contacts -- there.  You will have a wider ultimate audience here; for while the tide of life is magnificently

Caption-Abstract: Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)
Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)
Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)

element_texts.text: Completed

full strong in the west, the literary forces of life in this country are largely in the East & are going to be for more than one generation.  That means a calm, a depth, a soberness, a balance, a finish to work, a freedom from crudity -- & an absence of fiction, that are all invaluable & that tell more than most men realize until they are old.  
Aside from your work as a teacher, you are doing a missionary work right here that is invaluable.  I do not doubt it is done under such discouragements & annoyances & perhaps apparent lack of appreciation.  But no form of labor was excepted from the "Sweat of thy brow" condition: & it is the New England way to say little or nothing if there are no complaints -- to us unclear.  
But you have here marked the beginning of the change in Congregationalism from a group of churches that give the gospel to those that will support it

Caption-Abstract: Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)
Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)
Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)

element_texts.text: Completed

into a home missionary body.  Look at what you are doing: or, better, in order that you may see it truly, at what God is doing through you.  Unclear dear Doctor, that is the true & only ----ology.  Let uss [sic] take care that we don't substitute scientific treatment for the giving of life to & for life.  
I shall hate to see you go.  for every reason.  There are many things one is tempted to say: but man has no business to put his darkness in the place of God's light.  I am sure you will get that.  But I may & do pray that it will show your place here.  
Sincerely yours,
Jacob L. Greene
P.E.

Poquonock 
Conn. 
Dec. 27 1927 
My Dear Professor. 
Your delightful Christmas greeting was very very welcome.  It was addressed to Suffield our home of five years ago.  Most of my mail now comes to Windsor inasmuch as I am the Editor of the Windsor Herald.  President, also for we incorporated in

Caption-Abstract: Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)
Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)
Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)

element_texts.text: Completed

August.  It is a lot of fun after 50 years of pain to be able to work seven days a week evenings included & have my dreams come true.  I am sending the last issue of the Windsor Herald -- Windsor is rather proud of it & I am very happy in the work -- very happy.  The two girls & I & the two boys, although they are not married yet, have great times together.  My church people watch the paper with great interest -- they feel that my editorials 52 times a year more than make up for my calls.  May the New Year be the best, as it will be.  
As Ever  
Victor L. Greenwood

Dear Miss Hawkins --
Enclosed find money order in payment for Thru Forty Years" by Dr. Taylor.  I'm sorry and ashamed at my delay -- First I was so sure we would stop by some day and later we expected to be at the invitation of the Common's family.  At the last hour Dr. Gron was called on a new baby case so --  
Thru Forty Years is delightfully and sincerely written.  Every time I pick it up I can almost hear Dr. Taylor's voice.  I've found it a valuable history of Chicago life as well as the activities of the settlement work.  I'm so glad to have it for my own.  
I'm constantly grateful for the time spent with you all at the Commons.  
Ever sincerely,
Gertrude H--- Gron
(Mrs. Jas. Morgan)
1447 Foster Ave.
